Audiometer Main Screen Help
The main program window consists of three main elements:
· Pull-down menu
· Personal subject data
· Audiogram
The pull-down menu allows access to all user options of the program and is described here . The personal data section allows the entry of the name, date of birth, an employee reference number and a short comment. This data is saved together with the audiogram.
The personal data section allows the entry of the name, date of birth, an employee reference number and a short comment. This data is saved together with the audiogram.
The audiogram contains audiometric test data (if tested) in standard format according to ISO 8253-1: 1989. It can show the level traces from the so-called Bekesy test directly as well as the calculated average hearing threshold levels, depending on the program settings. If the test values vary beyond the tolerance levels for acceptable variation, diagonal hatching highlights the corresponding column in the audiogram.
In order to get a complete valid audiogram, retest these invalid columns by choosing ‘ Re-Test ’ from the ‘ Test ’ Menu.
File Menu Options
New
Deletes all current personal data and any measured audiogram. Choose this option to test a new subject.
Open
Displays a dialog box, where the user can choose a file name to re-open previously saved test data. This data can then be viewed, printed, compared with other tests or the subject can be tested again. Saved audiograms can also be opened by double clicking on them in the Windows Explorer similar to many other Windows applications.
Save
Displays a dialog box, where the user can choose a file name and then save the test and subject data to disk. The user can choose between two different file formats:
Normal Audiogram. This format saves all relevant data for use in the Home Audiometer software.
ASCII text . This format allows the user to export measured audiograms for use in other program, for example a spreadsheet, which might allow the user to compare and statistically analyse a number of different results.
Print
This option allows the user to print the subject data and the audiogram using any standard Windows compatible printer. The Printout is an exact copy of the main program window.
The best results are achieved using a colour printer.
Printer Set-up
Displays a standard Windows printer dialog box.
Settings
This program has got an extensive settings section, which makes it very flexible for different applications and user preferences. When the user presses the ‘ OK ’ button, the values are stored in the Windows Registry. The values are kept permanently and are not lost when the user exits and restarts the program.
The settings are divided into five different sections, which are described separately.
Calibration Menu Options
Load Calibration Data
A calibration performed and stored previously can be opened here. Double clicking on the .cal file in Windows Explorer also opens calibration data with Home Audiometer.
New Calibration by Ear
This option allows the user to calibrate the audiometer without the need for external calibration equipment. Remember: This is a substitute for a real calibration, and intrinsically not as precise. It is crucial to get the calibration right, if you want as accurate results as possible. Read here for a description of the calibration process.
Calibration - Check or Recalibrate
This option is similar to ‘ New Calibration ’ , but do not dismiss the currently loaded data. This makes it possible to check or correct a previous calibration.
This is particularly useful to check the stability and validity of a calibration setting over a longer period.
Calibration - Information
Shows the extra information saved with the currently loaded calibration data.
Test Menu
New Test
This dismisses the current test results and starts a new audiometric test using the parameters defined in the ‘ settings ’ section. Please note that this menu option is only active when the system has been calibrated or previous calibration data has been loaded. Click here for a detailed Test procedure description.
During a test, the trace of the currently tested frequency and the state of the subject response button can be seen in the real time trace window. All frequencies completed will be displayed immediately in the main audiogram.
If a test on one certain frequency lies outside the tolerance criteria for a valid result, it is marked and can then be re-tested.
Retest
Invalid results (due to inconsistent subject responses) of an audiometry test can be re-tested without the need for a complete test re-run. This can also be done automatically after each test by selecting ‘ Auto Retest ’ in the program settings This menu option is only active when the system has been calibrated or previous calibration data has been loaded.
Audiometry - View Results
This option displays the test results, calculates and shows the result category according to [1].
It also allows the user to print the results.
Test Procedure
The Test procedure can be customised by changing a range of parameters. These parameters are set to default values according to International Standard ISO 8253-1.
For best results leave the parameters as they are, unless you have specific reasons to change them.
Test frequencies Chooses the frequencies at which the subject is tested Signal duration Duration of a single tone pulse Gap duration Duration of the silence gap between two pulses Level steps Level difference between two pulses when going up or down in level. Initial level The hearing level in dB, at which the test procedure starts. Please note that a single frequency always starts at the same level the previous frequency ended. Maximum test duration Maximum length of the test for one frequency. If this time is reached, the test continues with the next frequency. If the minimum number of reversals have not been reached, the results are marked as invalid. If no maximum time should be given, set this to a very high value. Minimum test reversals Minimum number of reversals for one frequency. If this number is reached, the test continues with the next frequency. Trial run Starts with a trial run at 1kHz, which gives the subject time to become familiarised with the test procedure before the actual test. The trial run must be ended by the operator in front of the screen. Left ear first The left ear is tested first. Repeat @ 1kHz Left ear is tested twice at 1 kHz. This can give clues about the reliability of the replies of the test subject. The difference between the two results is given in the results section. Auto retest Automatically re-tests invalid results immediately after the initial test without the need for the operator to stand by or intervene. The tests are repeated until all results are recognised as valid.
Hardware
Soundcards
Choose the output and mixing device here. There is no need to change this unless you have more than one sound card in your system.
You can also open the Windows Multimedia Options here to check your sound cards.
Test Response Button
Choose the Control type here, either a Joystick/Game pad type device or the CTRL-Key on the keyboard. A Game pad is highly recommended, as it is quieter, more reliable and the test subject can sit away from the PC.
You can also test the Game pad here, the red dot should respond to button presses on the gaming device. There is also a direct link to the Windows Gaming Device Options.
File Handling
Sets default values for file names and file location used. This can simplify and standardise the data storage and processing.
Suggested file name This list gives the options of which filename will be suggested when saving the test data. Default drive and directory Selects the disk drive and directory where the data is saved.
Graph display
These options change the appearance of the audiogram and selects how the results are displayed.
Show level traces Switches the display of the level traces on and off. Show thresholds Switches the display of the calculated threshold levels on and off. Highlight inaccurate results Switches the highlighting of those results, which do not fulfil the criteria for valid results, on and off. Ignore first reversal According to ISO 8253-1: 1989 the first reversal should be ignored for the calculation of the threshold. This can be switched on and off. Update Audiometer during test Switches the real time display of the audiometer on and off. The real time display is compulsory for type 4 audiometers, but could lead to performance problems on slower computers. Graph colours Changes the colours of the audiogram.

FAQ
Which headphones, sound cards and Game pad do you recommend?
The best sound card/headphones combination I found is a SoundBlaster mp3+ USB Sound System and real audiometric headphones, Telephonics TDH39 ’ s or Sennheiser DT48.
I can also recommend (and use myself) Plantronics DSP-400 USB headphones , as they are high quality and they are independent of the sound card of your computer.
Due to the Windows driver concept and the flexibility of the program, a range of sound cards can be used. The minimum requirements for any sound card are:
- High-level headphone output,
- Build in Windows volume control and
- Low noise (Signal to noise ratio of at least about 80 dB, check with your sound card manual).
Some older Creative Sound Blaster AWE 32 and 64 are not suitable due to the high output noise level.
You can test your own hardware in the Compatibility Test , accessed from the main Menu in the Calibration section.
The Game pad I use is a Logitech Precision USB , but any other game pad should also work. At the time of writing they cost from about $10.
If you do not have a game controller, you can also use the CTRL-key on the keyboard.
How do I build a custom response button to replace the game port joystick?
If you want to use your own response button, this is the diagram of the circuit you need.
The resistors can be any value: I used 100K. This button is connected to the game port.
Remember: You will have to install the Windows driver for an analogue joystick (2-axis, 2 button), otherwise the software does not recognise the button.
I recommend you try using the software with an actual game port Joystick to ensure it works with your game port and then try your own response button.
How to Calibrate the Home Audiometer by Ear
This option allows the user to calibrate the audiometer without the need for external calibration equipment. Remember: This is a substitute for an objective instrument-based calibration, and intrinsically not as precise. It is crucial to get the calibration right if you want accurate results. It is recommended that the person who calibrates the audiometer this way has a set of recent results from a professional hearing test as a reference or, as a minimum, is known to have normal hearing and is preferably under 30 years old and not a regular clubber or user of a personal stereo!
Step-by-Step guide:
· Wear the audiometric headphones in the same manner as during a test in a quiet environment . If the cables are long enough, you could go into the next room or you might have to cover your computer with a blanket or bedding.
· Repeat the following steps for every frequency and side:
1. Type the known hearing level into the yellow box. If you don ’ t have any reference results, set all values to zero, limitations for this method see above!
2. Switch the (pulsating) test sound to ON and then change the output level by moving the volume sliders up and down until the level is in the middle between definetely hearable and definetely unhearable. This will define the hearing threshold. If you cannot hear anything even at the highest level, your sound card/headphone combination might not be suitable.
3. Click next to jump to the next frequency.
· At the end, an extra window comes up where you can add information and comments to the data before it is saved to disk. This is purely to make it easier to recognise and organize calibration files.
Hints :
· At any time, you can go back and check previous frequencies without losing any values already set. When finished with the left side the same slider settings will automatically be suggested for the same frequencies of the right side. This can speed the process up, because in most cases they are the same or very similar for both sides.
· Try your calibration by testing the calibrating person. If you have done everything correctly, you should get the hearing level values that were typed into the yellow box during calibration.
· Some sound cards and headphones (including the recommended Plantronics models) have bass/treble/EQ controls and bass boost or 3D effect on/off switches. Please set these to neutral or disable them, as they affect pure tone playback.
Calibration - Check or Recalibrate
This option is similar to ‘ New Calibration ’ , but do not dismiss the currently loaded data. This makes it possible to check or correct a previous calibration.
This is particularly useful to check the stability and validity of a calibration setting over a longer period.
Audiometric Test Procedure (New Test)
The current test results are dismissed and a new audiometric test using the parameters defined in the ‘ settings ’ section is started. Please note that this menu option is only active when the system has been calibrated or previous calibration data has been loaded.
During a test, the trace of the currently tested frequency and the state of the subject response button can be seen in the real time trace window. All frequencies completed will be displayed immediately in the main audiogram.
If a test on one certain frequency and ear lies outside the tolerance criteria for a valid result, it is marked and can then be re-tested.
Hints:
· If the operator and the subject are one person, i.e. you are testing yourself, make sure you are NOT watching the computer monitor during the test, because this would almost certainly give you so many hints for the tone, that the test result would be meaningless.
· If you are testing yourself, you can start the actual test with the subject ’ s respond-button. Please follow the information on the pop-up screens.
Needed for testing your hearing:
In terms of additional hardware you will need a pair of Headphones. Also recommended is a Joystick (or Gamepad, USB or Gameport) as subject response button. See the FAQ how to build a custom response button.
The software runs on any 32-bit Windows computer (95/98/ME/NT/2000/XP). A Pentium 100 or equivalent with 16MB memory is recommended for real-time audiogram display during the test procedure. Due to the size of the on-screen audiograms a screen resolution of at least 800x600 is required and at least 256 colours are recommended.
The test must be done in a Quiet Room , i.e. best next door from your computer with extension leads, unless you have exceptionally quiet fans in your PC. You can also cover your computer with bedding or a blanket, but make sure your PC does not overheat!
Due to the Windows driver concept and the flexibility of the program, a range of Sound Cards can be used. The minimum requirements for any sound card are DA-Converter, Mixer unit and a S/N ration of at least about 80 dB.
You can test your hardware in the Compatibility Test , accessed from the main Menu in the Calibration section.
Any graphical Windows compatible Printer is supported and for best printing results, a colour printer is recommended.
What is an Audiometer?
An audiometer is a device that can measure a persons hearing, i.e. if their hearing is normal or impaired in any way (various degrees of deafness). The measurement can then give an indication of what might have caused the impairment (noise, age etc.)
Most people have had an ear test done at some point of their life, at school, their workplace, national service or their ENT doctor.
The most commonly used scientific method used is to play low level pure tone ‘ beeps ’ (sine wave) at different frequencies (tone pitch) with varying levels to the test subject, and the person responds by pressing a button if the tone was heard (Bekesy Test). This is repeated several times to then get a reliable average.
The results for each are measured in D eci b el H earing L evel, where 0 dBHL represents ‘ normal ’ hearing level for each frequency, 10 dB is still not unusual, and from about 50dB one can talk about serious impairments, which would not have gone unnoticed.
Professional audiometers have an accuracy of within 5 dB, and so has the professional edition of this software. This home edition can get within 10-15 dB of the true hearing level.
The professional edition of this software can be turned into a professional audiometer, when used with suitable hardware. Previous audiometry software written by the author was used at a British university for high frequency audiometry research, because it was the only tool suitable and flexible enough for their research.
At the same time, the home edition is meant as a relatively cheap tool that allows everybody at home to get a good idea about his or her hearing abilities.
These are some of the things you can find out about your hearing with this audiometer:
Noise induced, permanent hearing loss
If you have a noise induced hearing impairment, this will show up on an audiogram as a dip in the 4 Kilohertz region, i.e. your hearing is worse at 4000 Hertz than it is above and below.
A typical symptom of rifle shooting is noise induced hearing damage on the ear close to the gun. This is called Permanent Threshold Shift (PTS)
Temporary hearing loss
Test yourself before and after e.g. a loud concert or an evening out in a nightclub. You should notice a difference in your hearing level, which normally disappears after a few days. This is called Temporary Threshold Shift (TTS).
Age related hearing loss (Presbyacousis)
Compare your hearing to an older our younger member of your family, friends or colleagues.
By nature, the hearing of humans gets worse with age starting at the high frequencies.

Software Description and Features
The Home Audiometer Hearing Test Windows software turns your PC into a machine you can use to test your hearing through a standard sound card. While this is clearly not as accurate as a professional audiometer, it can give a good indication if there is a hearing problem or not. (The accuracy is 10-15 dB compared to 5dB accuracy of a professional meter over a total hearing range of 70dB, so worse by a factor of 2-3.)
Features include:
- Test procedure to ISO standards;
- Graphical display of results;
- System is calibrated by ear without external hardware;
- Data analysis and categorisation;
Registered users are eligible to unlimited updates when they are released.

Compatibility Test
This test is able to help you to determine if your sound card and headphones are suitable for use with Home Audiometer.
Use the volume slider on the left to vary the output volume, and the frequency slider in the middle to vary the pitch of the tone. Test tones should be generated at different tone levels (yellow field) from zero Decibels (loud) to – 60 Decibles (barely audible).
If your hardware is suitable, you should be able to find settings with the volume sliders at which you can still hear the tone pulses (even though at – 60 dB the tones will be very quiet) without getting any background noise/hiss. The very quiet tones are the crucial point of this exercise, because the Audiometer will generate tones near your hearing threshold during the test to see if your hearing is OK or not.
If you find that the tones at -60 dB are too low or too noisy I would recommend buying a pair of USB headphones. These have a ‘ sound card ’ (Digital to Analog converter) integrated and have been proven to work very well with this software. See here for more details.
Some sound cards and headphones (including the recommended Sound Blaster USB Device and Plantronics headphones) have bass/treble/EQ controls and bass boost or 3D effect on/off switches. Please set these to neutral or disable all effects and equalizers , as they affect pure tone playback.
